WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:04.240
You know, think back to high school or maybe college.

00:04.800 --> 00:09.280
You're sitting there staring at an essay prompt, and you've basically made your point.

00:09.400 --> 00:09.720
Right.

00:09.940 --> 00:16.260
You've argued your thesis, you've provided the evidence, and you've done it all in like three clear, tight paragraphs.

00:16.460 --> 00:19.480
Yeah, but the syllabus says the requirement is a minimum of five pages.

00:19.700 --> 00:20.200
Exactly.

00:20.600 --> 00:21.440
So what do you do?

00:21.800 --> 00:23.360
The academic padding begins.

00:23.740 --> 00:27.780
You know, the font size miraculously goes up to a 12.5.

00:27.780 --> 00:30.220
The margins get just a little bit wider.

00:30.560 --> 00:34.820
Yeah, and your vocabulary suddenly becomes incredibly Victorian.

00:35.100 --> 00:40.920
Suddenly a simple word like therefore becomes this massive architectural structure,

00:41.040 --> 00:45.240
like as a direct and unavoidable consequence of the aforementioned factors.

00:45.540 --> 00:48.480
Which is funny because you aren't actually adding any new thoughts.

00:48.620 --> 00:49.160
No, not at all.

00:49.240 --> 00:50.120
You're just adding fluff.

00:50.680 --> 00:54.760
I mean, you figure the teacher or the professor will look at the sheer physical weight of the text and think,

00:55.120 --> 00:57.140
wow, they really thought deeply about that.

00:57.140 --> 01:00.160
You are trying to simulate the physical appearance of hard work.

01:00.240 --> 01:00.400
Right.

01:00.560 --> 01:04.500
You're conflating the volume of the output with the quality of the thought process,

01:04.740 --> 01:08.100
mainly because, well, that's what the grading structure incentivized.

01:08.100 --> 01:16.940
And the fascinating and honestly slightly terrifying thing is that our most advanced artificial intelligence models are currently doing the exact same thing.

01:17.300 --> 01:18.280
Welcome to the Deep Dive.

01:18.360 --> 01:18.900
Glad to be here.

01:19.080 --> 01:25.480
The reason we're tackling this today is because we have two incredible sources on the table that completely,

01:25.880 --> 01:29.860
just completely upend how we think about artificial intelligence.

01:29.940 --> 01:30.620
Really do.

01:30.620 --> 01:38.160
First, we have a highly practical empirical piece of research by Bownhar and colleagues called Shorter But Not Worse.

01:38.660 --> 01:40.720
They notice a bizarre AI behavior.

01:40.900 --> 01:49.260
And second, we have our main focus, which is a massive, profound theoretical paper from June 2026 by a researcher named Fliction,

01:49.480 --> 01:54.560
titled The Substance and Accident of Reasoning, Admissibility, Repair, and the Geometry of Verbosity.

01:54.560 --> 01:57.860
Yeah, Bownhar's paper kind of provides the inciting incident here.

01:58.100 --> 01:58.180
Right.

01:58.340 --> 02:00.740
They discovered something completely counterintuitive.

02:01.540 --> 02:07.940
They found that if you take an AI model that's struggling with complex math and you actively make its training data easier,

02:08.180 --> 02:13.260
it actually makes the AI's reasoning more efficient, more accurate, and much more concise.

02:13.580 --> 02:14.640
Which is wild.

02:14.740 --> 02:15.380
It is.

02:15.720 --> 02:20.020
And Fliction's paper steps back from that empirical finding and asks, well, why?

02:20.240 --> 02:23.660
What is the actual geometry of thought that makes that possible?

02:23.660 --> 02:26.460
Because, I mean, that makes no sense on the surface.

02:26.720 --> 02:29.080
You'd think harder training makes a smarter AI.

02:29.480 --> 02:32.060
Like, if I want to get better at chess, I shouldn't play against novices.

02:32.200 --> 02:33.660
That's the logical assumption, yeah.

02:34.020 --> 02:40.220
But Fliction uses this anomaly to explore the literal geometry of how knowledge is stored.

02:40.960 --> 02:46.320
So we're going to understand why these models, and let's be honest, perhaps our own human minds,

02:47.020 --> 02:49.740
mistake the appearance of hard work for actual intelligence.

02:49.820 --> 02:51.140
It's a huge shift in perspective.

02:51.140 --> 02:53.560
So, to you listening right now, think about this.

02:54.540 --> 02:58.780
Have you ever padded an email to your boss with extra industry jargon,

02:58.980 --> 03:01.780
just to make it look like you spent an hour on it instead of five minutes?

03:01.800 --> 03:02.500
We've all done it.

03:02.760 --> 03:03.460
Yeah, we have.

03:03.980 --> 03:09.900
Well, today, you're going to learn exactly why machine learning models fall into that exact same trap.

03:10.100 --> 03:12.940
So, where do we start with this?

03:12.940 --> 03:20.080
To really diagnose why this verbosity emerges, we have to look at the baseline problem in how these models are trained.

03:20.660 --> 03:24.980
Specifically, the reinforcement learning pipelines for mathematical reasoning.

03:25.100 --> 03:25.940
Okay, the pipelines.

03:26.060 --> 03:26.300
Right.

03:26.300 --> 03:31.660
When developers train a model to solve math, they run it through thousands of problems,

03:31.860 --> 03:35.460
and very quickly, they run into a wall with the easy problems.

03:35.560 --> 03:37.040
Okay, let's unpack that for a second.

03:37.380 --> 03:40.420
When you say they run into a wall, you mean the model gets too good at them?

03:40.500 --> 03:41.260
Basically, yeah.

03:41.260 --> 03:47.440
Like, if you give an advanced AI a problem like solving for X in a basic algebraic equation,

03:47.760 --> 03:52.580
every single time it tries to answer what they call a rollout in the industry, right?

03:52.620 --> 03:53.340
Yes, a rollout.

03:53.380 --> 03:53.520
Right.

03:53.520 --> 03:57.140
So, every single rollout, it gets it right, it's hitting a 100% success rate.

03:57.260 --> 03:57.680
Mm-hmm.

03:58.260 --> 03:59.440
Why is that a wall?

03:59.660 --> 04:00.540
Isn't that the goal?

04:00.760 --> 04:06.640
Well, it is the goal for the end user, sure, but it is a total nightmare for the training algorithm.

04:06.680 --> 04:12.140
Because in reinforcement learning, a model learns by comparing its good attempts against its bad attempts.

04:12.620 --> 04:14.400
The algorithm looks at the difference.

04:14.760 --> 04:16.980
That difference is the mathematical gradient.

04:17.300 --> 04:18.080
The gradient, right?

04:18.080 --> 04:27.440
Yeah, so if every single attempt gets the exact same perfect score of 1.0, that gradient collapses to zero, there's no delta.

04:27.680 --> 04:28.160
Oh, I see.

04:28.420 --> 04:35.820
There is no difference between its attempts, which means the math literally cannot update the neural network's weights.

04:36.260 --> 04:38.240
The model learns absolutely nothing new.

04:38.520 --> 04:42.460
It's like a professional tennis player practicing against a wall.

04:42.640 --> 04:43.640
That's a great way to put it.

04:43.640 --> 04:47.860
They aren't going to improve their backhand because the environment isn't forcing them to adapt.

04:48.640 --> 04:49.880
There's no dynamic feedback.

04:50.580 --> 04:51.960
So what do the engineers do?

04:52.060 --> 04:55.780
Do they just delete the easy problems from the training data?

04:55.960 --> 04:57.140
That is exactly what they do.

04:57.260 --> 05:01.800
They filter out the easy problems because they provide no, quote, optimization signal.

05:02.020 --> 05:02.340
Wow.

05:02.440 --> 05:07.380
They force the model to concentrate exclusively on problems of intermediate and high difficulty.

05:07.760 --> 05:11.820
You know, places where the model still occasionally fails, thus preserving that vital gradient.

05:11.820 --> 05:13.920
But this is where the trap is set, right?

05:14.340 --> 05:18.160
Because think about what hard math problems naturally require.

05:18.300 --> 05:19.680
They require a lot of steps.

05:19.880 --> 05:20.280
Exactly.

05:20.800 --> 05:24.060
They require very long, complex strings of text to solve.

05:24.500 --> 05:30.340
If you are doing advanced calculus or proving a topological theorem, you can't just spit out the number four.

05:30.440 --> 05:33.980
No, you have to show 20 lines of painstaking work.

05:33.980 --> 05:41.420
So the model is now operating in an environment where it only ever sees a reward when it produces a long sequence of text.

05:41.640 --> 05:47.020
And over time, the model's neural network draws a really dangerous statistical correlation.

05:47.240 --> 05:53.120
It begins to associate the reward of getting the right answer strictly with the verbosity of a long answer.

05:53.200 --> 05:54.080
It's Pavlovium.

05:54.200 --> 05:54.740
Ring the bell.

05:54.940 --> 05:55.540
Get the food.

05:55.760 --> 05:57.040
Write a huge block of text.

05:57.160 --> 05:57.760
Get the reward.

05:58.100 --> 05:58.620
Precisely.

05:59.080 --> 06:02.320
But Fliction points out that it goes deeper than just classical conditioning.

06:02.780 --> 06:05.500
There is an information theoretic trap happening here.

06:05.660 --> 06:05.900
Okay.

06:06.040 --> 06:07.060
Information theoretic.

06:07.160 --> 06:07.400
Yeah.

06:07.540 --> 06:11.340
The paper talks heavily about the chain rule of conditional entropy.

06:11.660 --> 06:12.920
I want to try to puzzle this out.

06:13.020 --> 06:15.900
So conditional means based on what came before.

06:16.140 --> 06:16.420
Right.

06:16.840 --> 06:19.740
And entropy is a measure of randomness or uncertainty.

06:20.200 --> 06:20.540
Yes.

06:20.540 --> 06:27.080
Are you saying the AI just keeps talking because every new word limits the statistical randomness of the next word?

06:27.760 --> 06:28.780
Mechanically, yes.

06:29.280 --> 06:33.040
What's happening is rooted in how autoregressive models generate text.

06:33.520 --> 06:37.880
They predict the next word based on all the previous words, which is called the prefix.

06:38.180 --> 06:38.640
The prefix.

06:38.860 --> 06:39.000
Okay.

06:39.080 --> 06:49.400
So the chain rule of conditional entropy states that the entropy of Y given X1 and X2 is generally less than or equal to the entropy of Y given just X1.

06:49.600 --> 06:50.880
Let's put that in plain English.

06:50.880 --> 06:55.820
In plain English, the more context you provide, the less uncertain the final answer becomes.

06:55.820 --> 07:03.400
Generating a longer prefix can only decrease or at worst preserve the mathematical uncertainty of your final answer.

07:03.600 --> 07:04.780
Let me see if I have this right.

07:04.840 --> 07:08.320
If I start a sentence with, um, the capital of France is Vichy.

07:08.320 --> 07:12.280
There is a tiny bit of entropy there.

07:12.340 --> 07:12.600
Sure.

07:12.740 --> 07:16.560
It's almost certainly Paris, but maybe I'm talking about a historical period where it was Vichy.

07:16.700 --> 07:16.920
Right.

07:17.140 --> 07:24.640
But if I write the capital of France where the Eiffel Tower is located is, uh, I have reduced the entropy to absolute zero.

07:24.860 --> 07:25.720
It has to be Paris.

07:25.720 --> 07:27.340
That is a perfect illustration.

07:28.180 --> 07:34.640
So if there is no penalty for taking up space, the AI learns to use verbosity as a statistical shortcut.

07:34.900 --> 07:35.280
Oh, wow.

07:35.540 --> 07:47.940
It pads its output with meaningless filler or overly complex step-by-step logic simply to drive the mathematical uncertainty of the final output token as close to zero as possible.

07:47.940 --> 07:50.160
It's optimizing for predictability.

07:50.400 --> 07:50.960
Exactly.

07:51.280 --> 07:53.280
And the engineers look at that and say, well, great.

07:53.440 --> 07:54.820
The model is reducing entropy.

07:55.100 --> 07:56.260
Uncertainty is going down.

07:56.300 --> 07:58.460
So the model is getting smarter and more confident.

07:58.780 --> 07:59.060
Yeah.

07:59.160 --> 08:00.960
That's the standard industry assumption.

08:01.560 --> 08:04.100
But Flixion pushes back on this incredibly hard.

08:04.240 --> 08:04.700
How so?

08:05.060 --> 08:08.020
Flixion argues that entropy reduction is not intelligence.

08:08.280 --> 08:08.420
Okay.

08:08.420 --> 08:13.600
The conventional argument only identifies the mechanism of why verbosity emerges.

08:13.840 --> 08:17.080
It completely fails to identify what is actually wrong with it.

08:17.620 --> 08:27.060
And Flixion provides three vivid analogies to illustrate why blindly optimizing for reduced uncertainty can actually destroy a complex system.

08:27.520 --> 08:32.860
Let's walk through those analogies because they really, uh, they really crystallize the danger of this mindset for me.

08:32.880 --> 08:33.420
They're very helpful.

08:33.420 --> 08:35.780
The first one Flixion uses is about language.

08:35.780 --> 08:40.980
Imagine a language that wants to reduce uncertainty so it starts merging words together.

08:41.300 --> 08:44.440
It collapses distinct meanings into a single semantic form.

08:44.680 --> 08:44.800
Right.

08:45.120 --> 08:52.760
If you force a language to merge words to narrow the distribution of interpretations, you end up with something highly predictable.

08:53.280 --> 08:56.220
It's literally George Orwell's newspeak from 1984.

08:56.620 --> 08:57.180
Exactly.

08:57.520 --> 09:03.880
You get rid of words like excellent, splendid, sublime, and you just force everyone to use double plus good.

09:04.060 --> 09:04.420
Yeah.

09:04.420 --> 09:09.280
Sure, you've reduced the statistical uncertainty of what word someone's going to use next.

09:09.380 --> 09:09.560
Yeah.

09:09.820 --> 09:16.400
But you've made actual disambiguation, the ability to express complex, nuanced reality, impossible.

09:16.920 --> 09:17.780
You've broken the tool.

09:17.980 --> 09:20.040
The system became predictable but useless.

09:20.340 --> 09:20.840
Useless, yeah.

09:20.920 --> 09:22.420
The second analogy is a map.

09:22.740 --> 09:25.100
Think about how you reduce uncertainty on a map.

09:25.220 --> 09:26.100
You erase the roads.

09:26.220 --> 09:26.440
Right.

09:26.620 --> 09:27.700
You erase the roads.

09:27.700 --> 09:36.000
If I erase all the side streets, the back alleys, the dirt roads, and I only leave the main highway, it is incredibly easy to predict where a driver is going to go.

09:36.340 --> 09:38.720
The entropy of their road is virtually zero.

09:39.120 --> 09:39.640
But wait.

09:39.880 --> 09:43.060
I can hear someone listening right now pushing back on this logic.

09:43.120 --> 09:43.440
Go ahead.

09:43.440 --> 09:50.040
Because if I'm building an autonomous driving system or a GPS, isn't predictability exactly what I want?

09:50.300 --> 09:51.720
I want the car to stay on the highway.

09:52.060 --> 09:56.280
Why is erasing the side streets bad if the highway gets you to the destination?

09:56.740 --> 09:57.860
It's a fair question.

09:58.060 --> 10:00.580
But think about what happens when the environment changes.

10:00.580 --> 10:07.900
If there is a massive traffic jam on the highway or a bridge collapses, the driver is doomed.

10:08.440 --> 10:10.420
Oh, because the map doesn't show any other way around.

10:10.580 --> 10:11.060
Exactly.

10:11.520 --> 10:13.660
The map has lost its navigational capacity.

10:14.420 --> 10:18.480
The relevant quantity and intelligence is not predictability or low entropy.

10:18.860 --> 10:21.100
It is what Flitching calls admissibility.

10:21.600 --> 10:22.200
Admissibility.

10:22.580 --> 10:24.800
This is the cornerstone of the paper's theory.

10:25.220 --> 10:26.320
Definition 3.1.

10:26.580 --> 10:29.060
What exactly makes a representation admissible?

10:29.060 --> 10:34.800
A representation is admissible when it preserves the distinctions required for future action.

10:35.100 --> 10:37.520
Preserves the distinctions required for future action.

10:38.240 --> 10:41.640
So, keeping the side streets on the map because you might need them later,

10:42.020 --> 10:44.880
even if they make predicting the immediate route slightly harder.

10:45.300 --> 10:45.860
Exactly.

10:46.120 --> 10:50.060
You sacrifice a little bit of immediate predictability to maintain robustness.

10:50.160 --> 10:51.020
That makes total sense.

10:51.180 --> 10:54.980
And the third analogy brings it into human systems, a bureaucracy.

10:55.480 --> 10:56.400
Oh, I love this one.

10:56.400 --> 11:00.140
A bureaucracy reduces uncertainty by prohibiting choices.

11:00.640 --> 11:04.580
It constrains the action space until the outcomes are fully determined.

11:04.860 --> 11:07.080
You fill out form A, you get outcome B.

11:07.240 --> 11:09.960
No exceptions, no context considered.

11:10.480 --> 11:16.500
The uncertainty is gone, but it completely destroys the agency the system was ostensibly designed to support.

11:16.500 --> 11:20.420
The distinction of individual human circumstances is totally erased.

11:20.540 --> 11:20.740
Right.

11:21.040 --> 11:27.100
So, applying this back to the AI, by making all successful math solutions look long and verbose,

11:27.480 --> 11:30.780
the AI has reduced entropy at the cost of admissibility.

11:30.900 --> 11:31.320
Yes.

11:31.460 --> 11:36.640
It made itself predictable, but it lost the capacity to produce the full range of correct solutions.

11:36.780 --> 11:40.500
It traded true understanding for a highly specific, brittle proxy.

11:40.500 --> 11:51.620
Okay, so if entropy reduction is this, like false idol, what physically broke inside the AI model's brain when it learned to be so wordy?

11:51.660 --> 11:52.960
That's where we get into the geometry.

11:53.460 --> 11:53.640
Yeah.

11:53.780 --> 12:00.340
I want to get into the hidden geometry of how knowledge is soared, because Fliction talks about representational collapse,

12:00.680 --> 12:02.740
specifically a projection collapse.

12:02.740 --> 12:10.080
So, in a healthy, well-functioning neural network, the model maintains a multidimensional space of concepts.

12:10.660 --> 12:16.220
It knows that the correctness of an answer and the length of an answer are two entirely separate things.

12:16.300 --> 12:16.520
Okay.

12:17.120 --> 12:19.560
In mathematical terms, they are orthogonal.

12:19.900 --> 12:21.760
They sit at right angles to each other.

12:21.940 --> 12:23.340
Meaning they don't affect each other.

12:23.540 --> 12:24.020
Exactly.

12:24.260 --> 12:28.680
You can have short wrong answers, short right answers, long wrong answers, and long right answers.

12:28.860 --> 12:30.360
They are independent variables.

12:30.360 --> 12:33.140
Yes, but remember what happened during training.

12:33.500 --> 12:33.580
Right.

12:33.700 --> 12:41.020
The data only ever rewarded the model when it gave long correct answers, because all the easy problems were thrown out.

12:41.420 --> 12:44.700
So, the model's internal map literally merged the two concepts.

12:45.180 --> 12:51.220
The mathematical function of correct, f of correct, literally became conflated with the function of long, f of long.

12:51.340 --> 12:52.380
The distinction collapsed.

12:52.420 --> 12:53.440
The distinction collapsed.

12:53.940 --> 12:59.440
Fliction uses a specific geometric language to describe this, drawing on the CLIO framework.

12:59.440 --> 13:00.920
How does that work visually?

13:01.460 --> 13:03.020
Imagine a two-dimensional graph.

13:03.620 --> 13:06.360
The we-axis is quality, is the answer good or bad.

13:06.580 --> 13:09.640
The x-axis is length, is the answer short or long.

13:09.740 --> 13:10.080
Got it.

13:10.160 --> 13:11.360
A simple coordinate plane.

13:11.480 --> 13:11.700
Right.

13:12.080 --> 13:16.840
In this geometric space, fliction introduces the concept of a fiber.

13:17.060 --> 13:17.540
A fiber.

13:17.540 --> 13:20.500
A fiber is the pre-image of a good solution.

13:21.080 --> 13:30.820
It's the physical region on our graph, and corresponding to the literal matrix of weights in the neural network that represents all the valid ways to arrive at a correct answer.

13:30.940 --> 13:31.100
Okay.

13:31.200 --> 13:36.960
So, in an undistorted healthy representation, that fiber stretches all the way across the x-axis.

13:37.220 --> 13:37.740
Exactly.

13:37.740 --> 13:41.560
It contains both short correct trajectories and long correct trajectories.

13:41.760 --> 13:44.020
Because there are many valid ways to arrive at the truth.

13:44.240 --> 13:44.800
Some are brief.

13:45.160 --> 13:46.000
Some are exhaustive.

13:46.200 --> 13:51.360
But under the hard-only training curriculum, the empirical support for this fiber physically contracts.

13:51.780 --> 13:55.100
The entire short trajectory region of the fiber disappears.

13:55.320 --> 13:55.980
It just vanishes.

13:55.980 --> 14:02.500
The model's weights shift so drastically that it assigns near-zero probability to that area of the graph.

14:02.760 --> 14:05.060
So, it's not just that the model prefers long answers.

14:05.460 --> 14:12.300
It's that the matrix values for short and correct are literally indistinguishable or unattainable.

14:12.760 --> 14:17.100
The model cannot see or reach short correct solutions anymore.

14:17.640 --> 14:19.820
That part of its brain has just gone dark.

14:20.120 --> 14:22.680
It is a profound loss of navigational structure.

14:22.680 --> 14:30.500
A planner operating on a collapsed representation can no longer distinguish between properties that are necessary for success

14:30.500 --> 14:35.820
and properties that merely happen to accompany success in its limited past experience.

14:36.140 --> 14:42.300
Let me try to anchor this with a real-world analogy, because I want to make sure we really feel the weight of this collapse.

14:42.400 --> 14:42.740
Please do.

14:43.060 --> 14:45.400
Imagine a hiring manager at a tech company.

14:45.400 --> 14:54.900
Over the course of 10 years, purely by coincidence, every single software engineer who performed exceptionally well and got promoted also happened to wear glasses.

14:55.100 --> 14:58.260
A statistical anomaly in the training data of the manager's career.

14:58.420 --> 14:59.220
Right, exactly.

14:59.600 --> 15:01.880
So, initially, the manager might just notice a correlation.

15:02.580 --> 15:09.440
But over time, if the manager's brain undergoes a projection collapse, they stop looking at coding tests or performance metrics entirely.

15:09.440 --> 15:16.000
They begin to assume that wearing glasses is the literal substance of being a good engineer.

15:17.100 --> 15:18.500
The two concepts merge.

15:19.440 --> 15:22.620
F of good employee becomes F of wears glasses.

15:22.900 --> 15:32.000
And if we tie that back to the neural network, the weights in the manager's brain that evaluate competence have been entirely overwritten by the visual processing of eyewear.

15:32.220 --> 15:32.560
Yes.

15:32.720 --> 15:37.340
So what happens when a brilliant, perfect candidate walks in without glasses?

15:37.340 --> 15:40.320
The manager literally cannot see them as a good candidate.

15:40.420 --> 15:40.940
Exactly.

15:41.200 --> 15:44.520
The fiber representing good engineers without glasses has collapsed.

15:45.000 --> 15:47.220
The manager isn't just making a lazy choice.

15:47.720 --> 15:51.080
Their internal representation of reality has lost a vital dimension.

15:51.380 --> 15:57.240
They've mistaken an accidental property, eyewear, for the essential, substantial property of competence.

15:57.360 --> 16:02.260
Which opens up a massive can of worms regarding how the entire tech industry is operating right now.

16:02.280 --> 16:02.980
Oh, absolutely.

16:02.980 --> 16:08.800
Because this geometry of collapse doesn't just explain why an AI writes a novel to solve 2 plus 2.

16:09.080 --> 16:12.480
It reveals a systemic flaw in how we measure progress.

16:13.000 --> 16:20.040
Fliction lays this out in Proposition 5.1, defining the algebraic skeleton of these failures as a proxy collapse.

16:20.420 --> 16:20.740
Right.

16:21.300 --> 16:26.780
A proxy collapse occurs when a learner replaces a strong correlation with a strict identity.

16:27.040 --> 16:27.840
Okay, unpack that.

16:27.840 --> 16:35.380
Instead of saying proxy A predicts target B, the system begins to operate as if proxy A is target B.

16:35.440 --> 16:43.380
And Fliction identifies three distinct machine learning errors that are all, at their core, this exact same projection collapse.

16:43.540 --> 16:50.120
Yeah, we've talked deeply about one of them, the entropy reduction error or verbosity, where the model conflates correct reasoning with length.

16:50.240 --> 16:51.940
But the other two are everywhere right now.

16:52.280 --> 16:54.080
Let's look at the latent compression error.

16:54.080 --> 17:02.580
In machine learning architecture, developers frequently try to compress complex data into a lower-dimensional latent space to make the model run efficiently.

17:02.780 --> 17:03.840
Make it smaller and faster.

17:04.040 --> 17:04.240
Right.

17:04.940 --> 17:10.620
Historically, models that achieve this low dimensionality happen to generalize very well to new data.

17:11.200 --> 17:16.860
So the field began conflating a general, robust representation with a low-dimensional representation.

17:17.360 --> 17:20.960
They assumed lower dimensionality is inherently better, like smaller is smarter.

17:20.960 --> 17:21.580
Exactly.

17:21.940 --> 17:25.540
They treated the proxy low dimensions as the target itself.

17:25.680 --> 17:26.520
Which is a collapse.

17:26.860 --> 17:27.180
Yes.

17:27.600 --> 17:34.360
The problem is, eventually, you compress the data so heavily that you throw away vital nuances.

17:35.060 --> 17:40.020
You collapse distinctions that are actually required for navigating complex tasks.

17:40.100 --> 17:44.260
The model fails because it threw away the side streets to make a perfectly straight highway.

17:44.420 --> 17:44.960
That's it.

17:45.100 --> 17:45.300
Exactly.

17:45.300 --> 17:47.640
But the third error is the one that really caught my eye.

17:48.320 --> 17:50.320
Fliction calls it the reasoning length error.

17:51.040 --> 17:53.360
Conflating good reasoning with many steps.

17:53.680 --> 17:56.000
This is the cultural myth of long chains of thought.

17:56.220 --> 17:57.480
I mean, I see this everywhere.

17:57.700 --> 17:59.200
Oh, it's the dominant narrative.

17:59.460 --> 18:03.820
You go on tech blogs, and everyone is hyping up test-time compute scaling.

18:04.280 --> 18:09.220
They post screenshots of an AI taking 400 steps to answer a logic puzzle, and they say,

18:09.380 --> 18:10.660
look how deep it's thinking.

18:11.080 --> 18:12.640
It's reasoning just like a human.

18:12.640 --> 18:18.500
The entire discourse assumes that an AI that takes 10 steps to answer is inherently thinking

18:18.500 --> 18:20.920
deeper than one taking two steps.

18:21.020 --> 18:22.840
It is a massive cultural delusion.

18:23.060 --> 18:27.900
Fliction brings in philosophical terminology to explain why we are being fooled by this.

18:28.140 --> 18:28.840
Let's hear it.

18:28.840 --> 18:35.000
These properties, low dimensions, low entropy, many steps, they are what philosophers call

18:35.000 --> 18:36.720
accidental properties.

18:36.980 --> 18:37.220
Accidental.

18:37.520 --> 18:37.800
Yes.

18:38.120 --> 18:43.040
They are contingent on the specific bias training data the models were fed.

18:43.340 --> 18:45.020
They are not substantial properties.

18:45.300 --> 18:48.240
They do not constitute the actual essence of intelligence.

18:48.500 --> 18:49.900
Substance versus accident.

18:50.000 --> 18:51.700
That's literally the title of the paper.

18:51.900 --> 18:52.320
It is.

18:52.320 --> 18:56.220
We are looking at the accidental byproducts of the training environment and worshipping

18:56.220 --> 18:58.200
them as the substance of intelligence.

18:58.340 --> 18:59.640
That's a great way to summarize it.

19:00.040 --> 19:05.160
So, wait, are you saying that if a two-step correct proof exists and the AI pads it out

19:05.160 --> 19:09.780
to 10 steps, that is not a sign of deep thought, but actually a sign of structural brain damage

19:09.780 --> 19:10.300
in the model?

19:10.680 --> 19:11.140
I am.

19:11.500 --> 19:17.520
A model that produces 10 reasoning steps when two would suffice is not engaging in careful

19:17.520 --> 19:18.000
reasoning.

19:18.560 --> 19:21.160
It is trapped in an inadmissible representation.

19:21.560 --> 19:22.040
Wow.

19:22.320 --> 19:26.700
It is the student adding five pages of fluff because it literally doesn't know how to just

19:26.700 --> 19:28.840
be right and be concise at the same time.

19:29.300 --> 19:31.020
The models aren't failing to learn.

19:31.380 --> 19:35.640
They are succeeding perfectly at learning the wrong lessons from flawed data.

19:35.900 --> 19:36.120
Okay.

19:36.220 --> 19:37.640
So, we've diagnosed the disease.

19:38.120 --> 19:40.340
The model's internal geometry has collapsed.

19:40.740 --> 19:42.480
It's blindly following proxies.

19:42.880 --> 19:46.140
Its fiber of short solutions has been totally obliterated.

19:46.200 --> 19:46.540
Yes.

19:46.920 --> 19:47.960
How do we fix it?

19:47.960 --> 19:52.300
I mean, my immediate instinct, and probably the instinct of anyone listening, is to

19:52.300 --> 19:53.060
just to punish it.

19:53.380 --> 19:54.440
That's the usual route.

19:54.580 --> 19:54.860
Right.

19:55.460 --> 19:58.160
If the AI is talking too much, dock its points.

19:58.820 --> 20:04.900
Put a length penalty in the code, like minus 0.1 from the reward for every extra word.

20:05.220 --> 20:07.160
Why doesn't a simple length penalty work?

20:07.160 --> 20:12.020
That is the standard intuitive approach in the field, penalty-based regularization.

20:12.780 --> 20:18.040
But Flickshinen, drawing heavily on Bownhar et al.'s empirical data, proves why penalties

20:18.040 --> 20:20.580
are mathematically and geometrically inadequate.

20:20.960 --> 20:21.200
Okay.

20:21.260 --> 20:24.620
The intervention from the shorter but not worse paper was astonishing.

20:25.040 --> 20:27.760
To fix the AI, they didn't add a single length penalty.

20:27.960 --> 20:29.100
They didn't penalize it at all?

20:29.140 --> 20:29.620
Not at all.

20:29.680 --> 20:33.480
They simply mixed moderately easy math problems back into the training data.

20:33.600 --> 20:34.800
They just gave it some easy homework?

20:34.920 --> 20:35.220
Yes.

20:35.220 --> 20:35.840
And what happened?

20:36.320 --> 20:40.840
The AI solution length was cut in half across the board, even on the profoundly hard problems,

20:41.040 --> 20:42.900
with zero loss in accuracy.

20:43.260 --> 20:44.300
That is wild.

20:44.500 --> 20:46.380
The brevity was entirely emergent.

20:46.600 --> 20:48.200
It basically healed itself.

20:48.320 --> 20:50.320
It just naturally decided to stop waffling.

20:50.640 --> 20:52.760
But I need to understand the mechanics here.

20:53.100 --> 20:59.440
Flickshinen formalizes this in Theorem 6.1, calling it easy problems as minimal repair.

20:59.700 --> 20:59.960
Right.

20:59.960 --> 21:03.960
I want you to explain this to me like I'm a first-year computer science student.

21:04.320 --> 21:09.860
We have to look at the mathematical advantage function the AI uses, specifically GRPO.

21:10.240 --> 21:11.920
Group relative policy optimization.

21:12.360 --> 21:12.540
Yeah.

21:12.740 --> 21:13.900
Break down that formula for me.

21:14.020 --> 21:16.540
Let's visualize the formula conceptually.

21:16.960 --> 21:21.180
The advantage function A determines how much the neural network updates its weights.

21:21.620 --> 21:21.900
Okay.

21:21.900 --> 21:27.020
The formula looks at a group of attempts, say 20 rollouts for a single math problem.

21:27.520 --> 21:31.200
It calculates the average reward of those 20 attempts, which we'll call the baseline.

21:31.400 --> 21:31.840
Makes sense.

21:31.840 --> 21:37.160
The advantage for any specific attempt is its individual reward minus that baseline,

21:37.420 --> 21:38.880
divided by the standard deviation.

21:39.560 --> 21:42.680
A equals R minus baseline, divided by standard depth.

21:42.840 --> 21:43.120
Okay.

21:43.240 --> 21:44.720
So it's standard grading on a curve.

21:45.120 --> 21:47.900
If I do better than the class average, my advantage is positive,

21:48.160 --> 21:50.400
and the neural pathways I use get strengthened.

21:50.740 --> 21:53.940
If I do worse, it's negative, and those pathways get weakened.

21:54.120 --> 21:54.660
Precisely.

21:54.940 --> 22:00.000
Now let's look at the fatal flaw on hard problems, what Flickshinen calls advantage blindness.

22:00.300 --> 22:01.040
Advantage blindness.

22:01.040 --> 22:04.220
Imagine the AI is given a brutally hard problem.

22:04.580 --> 22:07.600
Out of 20 attempts, it only gets the right answer twice.

22:08.320 --> 22:10.960
Both correct attempts receive a reward of 1.0.

22:11.320 --> 22:12.860
The other 18 get zero.

22:13.040 --> 22:15.260
So the baseline average is very low, like 0.1.

22:15.340 --> 22:15.560
Right.

22:15.880 --> 22:19.780
Now suppose one of those correct answers was incredibly concise, just two lines,

22:20.060 --> 22:24.680
and the other correct answer was a sprawling 50-line waffling mess.

22:24.940 --> 22:25.300
Okay.

22:25.420 --> 22:26.420
Let's run them through the formula.

22:26.600 --> 22:30.060
For the short answer, 1.0 minus 0.1.

22:30.060 --> 22:31.660
The advantage is highly positive.

22:31.660 --> 22:34.360
For the long answer, 1.0 minus 0.1.

22:34.520 --> 22:37.220
The advantage is identically highly positive.

22:37.340 --> 22:38.280
Oh, I see it.

22:38.620 --> 22:40.900
The math has no variable for word count.

22:41.040 --> 22:41.420
None.

22:41.580 --> 22:45.480
The grading curve gives them the exact same massive positive update.

22:45.840 --> 22:48.700
It literally receives no informational push to be concise.

22:48.700 --> 22:50.820
The system is structurally blind to length.

22:51.220 --> 22:52.360
That is advantage blindness.

22:52.980 --> 22:59.080
The objective function is mathematically incapable of teaching the policy to prefer short solutions on hard problems.

22:59.540 --> 23:03.580
Because short solutions are so rare, they just get lumped in with any successful trajectory.

23:04.000 --> 23:04.120
Wow.

23:04.120 --> 23:07.860
But now, look at what happens when you introduce easy problems.

23:08.380 --> 23:12.180
You create what Fliction calls a budget-truncated asymmetry.

23:12.580 --> 23:13.660
Budget truncation.

23:13.940 --> 23:14.120
Yeah.

23:14.220 --> 23:20.380
Meaning, there is a hard limit to how many tokens or words the AI is allowed to output before the system cuts it off.

23:20.580 --> 23:25.500
Every AI has an maximum context window or token budget per generation.

23:25.500 --> 23:30.660
Now, imagine the AI is given an easy problem, like solving 3x equals 12.

23:30.780 --> 23:31.280
Very easy.

23:31.440 --> 23:39.740
But because it has been deeply conditioned to be verbose, it attempts to write a massive, sprawling philosophical treatise on the nature of algebra.

23:39.920 --> 23:49.980
And because it's an easy problem, the philosophical treatise goes on for so long that it runs out of tokens, it hits the budget limit, and gets truncated before it actually outputs x equals 4.

23:50.020 --> 23:50.400
Exactly.

23:50.400 --> 23:56.300
It gets cut off, fails to provide the final answer, and receives a reward of 0, a failing grade.

23:56.580 --> 24:02.520
Meanwhile, on that same easy problem, maybe one of its random attempts was a short, direct answer.

24:03.020 --> 24:05.280
That attempt easily fits within the token budget.

24:05.640 --> 24:09.080
It provides the final answer, and it gets a full reward of 1.0.

24:09.420 --> 24:12.820
So on the easy problems, the grading curve finally separates the two.

24:12.940 --> 24:13.280
Yes.

24:13.380 --> 24:19.420
The short answer gets the 1.0, and the long, waffling answer hits the ceiling, gets truncated, and gets a 0.

24:19.420 --> 24:24.860
Easy problems finally provide the positive differential gradient to favor short solutions.

24:25.560 --> 24:32.240
They physically demonstrate to the model that a short, correct answer is not only possible, but highly successful.

24:32.680 --> 24:34.820
Okay, but this circles back to my question about penalties.

24:35.200 --> 24:39.860
In section 8 of the paper, Fliction talks about the information gap of length penalties.

24:40.020 --> 24:40.260
Right.

24:40.260 --> 24:44.480
Why is just subtracting points for long answers worse than this easy problem repair?

24:44.620 --> 24:49.580
If I add a penalty, couldn't I just alter the GRPO formula so the long answer gets a lower score?

24:49.920 --> 24:55.600
You could, but it comes down to corollaries 8.3 and 8.4 and the geometry of the collapsed fiber.

24:55.680 --> 24:56.460
Oh, back to the fiber.

24:56.820 --> 25:03.780
Remember, in a collapsed representation, the model literally does not know that short, correct answers are physically possible.

25:03.780 --> 25:07.560
The short trajectory region of its neural network has been overwritten.

25:08.020 --> 25:09.700
The probability is near zero.

25:10.120 --> 25:10.760
Right.

25:10.860 --> 25:17.680
It's the hiring manager who physically cannot perceive a good engineer unless they are wearing glasses.

25:18.000 --> 25:23.680
If you introduce a length penalty, all you are doing is telling the model long is bad.

25:23.920 --> 25:27.780
You are punishing the only behavior it currently knows how to execute successfully.

25:28.480 --> 25:28.780
Oh, hope.

25:28.780 --> 25:30.680
But you aren't showing it an alternative.

25:30.980 --> 25:33.160
You aren't repopulating the empty fiber.

25:33.360 --> 25:34.740
So the model just gets paralyzed.

25:35.160 --> 25:40.480
It says, I have to be long to be correct, but now I'm getting heavily penalized for being long.

25:40.560 --> 25:42.060
I literally don't know what else to do.

25:42.060 --> 25:47.780
A penalty just compresses the long solution region without expanding the short solution region.

25:47.920 --> 25:51.060
It penalizes the accident without demonstrating the substance.

25:51.240 --> 25:52.200
That makes perfect sense.

25:52.340 --> 25:55.060
As Fliction writes, repair dominates penalty.

25:55.060 --> 25:59.740
You have to demonstrate admissibility before the model has fully internalized that it cannot be done.

26:00.140 --> 26:07.780
Let's try to map this to a physical analogy because the difference between regularization, which is fixing the objective via a penalty,

26:08.340 --> 26:13.660
and morphological repair, which is fixing the representation, is huge.

26:13.780 --> 26:15.340
It's the core of the paper.

26:15.620 --> 26:22.000
Imagine you have a dog, and for its entire life, it has only ever been allowed to go into the backyard through the back door.

26:22.000 --> 26:29.300
However, in the dog's internal representation, the concept of going outside is perfectly conflated with the back door.

26:30.080 --> 26:31.340
The fiber has collapsed.

26:31.600 --> 26:32.960
A perfect proxy collapse.

26:33.100 --> 26:35.380
F of outside equals F of back door.

26:35.560 --> 26:35.840
Right.

26:36.100 --> 26:38.720
Now, you decide you want the dog to use the front door.

26:39.280 --> 26:43.280
The length penalty approach is like putting an invisible electric fence at the back door.

26:43.700 --> 26:45.780
When the dog tries to go out, it gets shocked.

26:46.220 --> 26:47.180
What does the dog learn?

26:47.320 --> 26:49.280
It certainly doesn't learn to use the front door.

26:49.280 --> 26:51.900
No. It just thinks it's trapped in the house forever.

26:52.380 --> 26:56.980
It's paralyzed. You've made its only known path painful without demonstrating an alternative.

26:57.240 --> 27:01.260
And in neural network terms, the penalty just pushes the weights toward negative infinity.

27:01.460 --> 27:02.640
It doesn't build a new pathway.

27:02.900 --> 27:09.840
But the easy problem repair, that is you walking over to the front door, opening it wide, and throwing a treat onto the front lawn.

27:09.920 --> 27:10.220
Yes.

27:10.220 --> 27:14.780
You demonstrate that a new, previously invisible path exists.

27:15.260 --> 27:17.660
You expand the dog's representation of reality.

27:18.160 --> 27:19.500
You repopulate the fiber.

27:19.800 --> 27:24.120
That is an exceptionally precise analogy for what Theorem 6.1 describes.

27:24.460 --> 27:26.600
The easy problems are the open front door.

27:27.080 --> 27:31.680
They provide admissibility evidence that the penalty approach fundamentally lacks.

27:31.820 --> 27:32.800
Okay. So you throw the treat.

27:33.000 --> 27:34.160
The dog goes through the front door.

27:34.600 --> 27:37.260
The AI solves the easy math problem concisely.

27:37.640 --> 27:38.800
The fiber is repaired.

27:38.800 --> 27:39.280
Yes.

27:39.560 --> 27:42.420
But moving forward, how do you maintain the cure?

27:43.100 --> 27:45.220
Does the dog remember the front door forever?

27:45.640 --> 27:53.680
Because eventually, the AI still has to solve those incredibly hard PhD-level math problems that genuinely do require long answers.

27:53.840 --> 27:54.780
That's a great point.

27:54.900 --> 27:59.160
If it learned that short is good, won't it just start giving short, wrong answers to hard problems?

27:59.260 --> 28:02.520
This is where the structural brilliance of the intervention really shines.

28:03.260 --> 28:05.340
Fliction details a two-stage curriculum.

28:05.520 --> 28:06.160
Okay. What's stage one?

28:06.440 --> 28:08.420
Stage one is what we just discussed.

28:08.800 --> 28:09.500
Emergent brevity.

28:09.560 --> 28:12.980
You feed it easy problems, and you physically repair the fiber.

28:13.600 --> 28:16.300
The model learns that shortness is a viable option.

28:16.500 --> 28:17.680
Stage one opens the front door.

28:17.900 --> 28:18.240
Exactly.

28:18.840 --> 28:23.960
Stage two is curriculum RLVR, or capability expansion into hard domains.

28:23.960 --> 28:29.020
Now you slowly start feeding it the brutally hard math problems again.

28:29.020 --> 28:33.060
And the incredible finding is stage two does not reintroduce the collapse.

28:33.060 --> 28:34.120
Wait, why not?

28:34.340 --> 28:40.060
If the hard problems only reward long answers again, why doesn't the gradient pull it right back into verbosity?

28:40.060 --> 28:43.120
Because the underlying geometry has fundamentally changed.

28:43.120 --> 28:49.160
Before stage one, the model conflated correctness and length into one single entangled variable.

28:49.380 --> 28:51.020
Right. F of correct was F of long.

28:51.200 --> 28:56.640
Now because of the easy problems, it understands that correctness and length are two separate orthogonal dimensions.

28:57.040 --> 29:02.480
So when it encounters a hard problem that genuinely requires a 50-step proof, it writes a 50-step proof.

29:02.540 --> 29:02.700
Whoa.

29:02.700 --> 29:10.880
But it does so only because the specific mathematical structure of the problem requires it, not out of a blind habitual proxy correlation.

29:11.220 --> 29:15.420
It's using the back door when the back door makes sense and the front door when the front door makes sense.

29:16.160 --> 29:17.580
It has agency again.

29:17.800 --> 29:18.220
Exactly.

29:18.540 --> 29:27.780
It can modulate its solution length based on the task, but fliction issues a major warning here in theorem 9.2, the stability condition.

29:28.020 --> 29:28.540
A warning?

29:28.540 --> 29:31.240
The repaired fiber requires active maintenance.

29:31.240 --> 29:44.300
Yes. Corollary 9.3 explicitly states that if you completely remove all easy problems in stage 2, if you go back to a strictly hard-only diet, the model will eventually relapse into verbosity.

29:44.500 --> 29:46.440
Wait, really? The fiber will contract again?

29:46.540 --> 29:46.860
Yes.

29:46.860 --> 29:56.980
The continuous presence of at least a small fraction of easy problems is mathematically required to provide the stabilizing gradient that keeps the short-solution fiber open.

29:57.120 --> 29:57.380
Wow.

29:57.380 --> 30:04.560
If you don't maintain the signal, the relentless pressure of the hard problems will slowly cause the projection to collapse all over again.

30:04.660 --> 30:05.540
Like muscle atrophy.

30:05.720 --> 30:06.560
Very much so.

30:06.640 --> 30:12.660
If you do heavy bench presses every single day but never stretch, eventually the joint tightens up and you lose your range of motion.

30:13.000 --> 30:16.680
You have to keep doing the light mobility work to maintain the joint's capacity.

30:17.020 --> 30:17.840
That's spot on.

30:17.840 --> 30:24.960
And this ties into a profound concept Fliction calls monotone correspondence in Proposition 9.4.

30:25.860 --> 30:34.840
Fliction connects the fiber admissibility gap, how much of the correct solution space the model is currently blind to, with something called reachability loss.

30:35.180 --> 30:36.220
What is reachability loss?

30:36.280 --> 30:43.400
It's a formal measure of how many successful futures a system permanently loses access to because of its rigid behavior.

30:43.520 --> 30:44.700
A loss of future potential.

30:44.700 --> 30:52.220
Exactly. The proposition proves that the bigger the blind spot in the model's representation, the greater the reachability loss.

30:52.760 --> 30:57.700
When a model collapses correctness into hubosity, it isn't just inefficient on current tasks.

30:58.060 --> 31:01.920
It literally cannot reach future deployment contexts where brevity is mandatory.

31:02.500 --> 31:06.560
It has sacrificed its future potential on the altar of its current training environment.

31:06.560 --> 31:11.220
So looking at the synthesis of all this, the golden rule seems to be repair before expansion.

31:11.740 --> 31:11.980
Absolutely.

31:12.240 --> 31:15.340
You cannot force a broken system to handle harder and harder tasks.

31:15.520 --> 31:18.120
You have to restore its local faithfulness first.

31:18.400 --> 31:23.200
You have to make sure its basic map of reality isn't conflating the accident with the substance.

31:23.720 --> 31:26.860
That is the universal principle of admissibility-based learning.

31:27.280 --> 31:32.120
If you try to expand a collapsed representation, you just magnify the collapse.

31:32.300 --> 31:35.640
Which brings us to the part of Fliction's paper that absolutely blew my mind.

31:35.640 --> 31:36.740
The broader implications.

31:37.020 --> 31:37.260
Yes.

31:37.880 --> 31:44.740
Fliction takes this highly specific, very modern mathematical fix in artificial intelligence and makes a stunning leap.

31:45.460 --> 31:53.400
The paper demonstrates that this morphological repair, repopulating an empty fiber by demonstrating a hidden distinction,

31:54.000 --> 31:59.860
is actually a universal pattern of how knowledge evolves across all of science, biology, and history.

31:59.860 --> 32:00.760
It really is.

32:01.120 --> 32:07.600
Fliction looks at three massive, real-world examples outside of AI to show that this is how all progress happens.

32:07.780 --> 32:14.160
Let's look at the scientific anomaly first, because the history of physics is essentially a history of projection collapses and subsequent repairs.

32:14.340 --> 32:14.800
Exactly.

32:15.000 --> 32:16.400
We're talking about Newton and Einstein.

32:16.940 --> 32:20.400
Let's walk through how Newtonian physics was suffering from a collapsed fiber.

32:20.680 --> 32:21.120
Please do.

32:21.120 --> 32:29.960
For centuries, classical Newtonian mechanics treated two fundamentally different concepts as the exact same thing, inertial mass and gravitational mass.

32:30.060 --> 32:31.060
Okay, let's define those.

32:31.360 --> 32:35.880
Inertial mass is a measure of how hard it is to accelerate an object when you push it.

32:36.280 --> 32:37.760
It's the M in F equals ma.

32:38.100 --> 32:38.380
Right.

32:38.740 --> 32:43.480
Gravitational mass is a measure of how heavily an object interacts with a gravitational field.

32:43.800 --> 32:47.180
It's the M in Newton's law of universal gravitation.

32:47.180 --> 32:51.720
So one is about resistance to a push, the other is about the pull of a planet.

32:52.440 --> 32:54.280
Conceptually, they are totally distinct.

32:54.500 --> 32:54.820
Yes.

32:55.280 --> 32:59.680
But under terrestrial conditions on Earth, they are perfectly proportional.

33:00.300 --> 33:04.900
If an object is twice as hard to push, it also weighs twice as much on a scale.

33:05.120 --> 33:11.440
So in the training data of human experience living on Earth, the two concepts correlated exactly.

33:11.600 --> 33:12.680
It was a projection collapse.

33:12.880 --> 33:13.400
Precisely.

33:13.400 --> 33:15.620
The scientific ontology merged them.

33:16.100 --> 33:18.260
F of inertial became F of gravitational.

33:18.580 --> 33:23.740
The scientific community became the hiring manager who thought wearing glasses was the same as being a good coder.

33:24.160 --> 33:27.820
They thought inertial resistance was the exact same substance as gravitational pull.

33:27.980 --> 33:28.220
Right.

33:28.480 --> 33:29.420
How did it get repaired?

33:29.820 --> 33:35.720
Through anomalies and extreme theoretical stress testing culminating in Einstein's general relativity,

33:36.540 --> 33:39.340
Einstein's equivalence principle forced the distinction open.

33:39.340 --> 33:45.140
The anomaly revealed that they are theoretically and geometrically distinct properties of space-time,

33:45.320 --> 33:47.440
even if they cover locally on Earth.

